devsecops Roadmap with daily task 

üìÖ Phase 1 ‚Üí Month 1 ‚Üí Week 1 (Linux Basics: Daily-Level Roadmap)
üéØ Goal: Understand Linux fundamentals, filesystem, permissions, processes, and searching.

Day 1 ‚Üí Linux Intro & Filesystem
- Topics:
	- What is Linux? Distros (Ubuntu, CentOS, Amazon Linux).
	- Filesystem hierarchy: /, /bin, /etc, /var, /usr, /tmp.
	- File types: regular, directory, symlink, device, socket.
- Commands: ls, pwd, cd, file, stat, tree.
- Practice:
	- Navigate Linux VM (AWS EC2 or local VM).
	- Use tree / | less ‚Üí explore directories.
- Mini-Task: Create linux_notes.md ‚Üí Document 10 commands + examples.
- Interview Prep:
	- What is the difference between /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow?
	- Explain Linux file types.

Day 2 ‚Üí File Operations
- Topics:
	- Creating/deleting: touch, rm.
	- Copying/moving: cp, mv.
	- Viewing: cat, less, head, tail, wc.
- Practice:
	- Create directory playground/ ‚Üí experiment with files.
	- Use tail -f /var/log/syslog to monitor logs in real time.
- Mini-Task: Write cheatsheet with 5 file viewing commands + options.
- Interview Prep:
	- How do you continuously monitor logs?
	- What‚Äôs the difference between cat and less?

Day 3 ‚Üí Permissions & Ownership
- Topics:
	- Permissions (r, w, x for user, group, others).
	- Changing permissions: chmod.
	- Ownership: chown, chgrp.
	- Special bits: SUID, SGID, Sticky Bit.
- Practice:
	- Create a shared folder ‚Üí test chmod 777, chmod 755.
	- Apply sticky bit ‚Üí only owner can delete.
- Mini-Task: Write table of permission values (644, 755, 700).
- Interview Prep:
	- Difference between symbolic (chmod u+x) and numeric (chmod 755) permissions?
	- Explain sticky bit with example.

Day 4 ‚Üí Processes & Jobs
- Topics:
	- Process lifecycle: foreground vs background.
	- Commands: ps, top, htop, jobs, fg, bg, kill, killall.
- Practice:
	- Run long job ‚Üí send to background with &.
	- Use kill -9 PID to stop process.
- Mini-Task: Document 5 ways to monitor processes.
- Interview Prep:
	- How do you find which process uses the most memory?
	- Difference between kill and killall?

Day 5 ‚Üí Links (Hard vs Soft)
- Topics:
	- Hard links vs symbolic links.
	- Commands: ln, ln -s.
- Practice:
	- Create file ‚Üí make hard link + soft link.
	- Delete original ‚Üí observe behavior of both.
- Mini-Task: Screenshot example of hard vs soft link test.
- Interview Prep:
	- What happens to hard/soft links when the original is deleted?

Day 6 ‚Üí Search & Regex
- Topics:
	- File search: find, locate.
	- Command search: which, whereis.
	- Text search: grep, egrep, regex basics.
- Practice:
	- Find all .log files in /var/log/.
	- Use grep -i "error" /var/log/syslog.
- Mini-Task: Write 3 regex patterns: email, IP, date.
- Interview Prep:
	- Difference between grep, egrep, and fgrep?
	- How to find all .sh files modified in last 24 hours?

Day 7 ‚Üí Weekly Recap + Mini-Project
- Tasks:
	- Review all topics ‚Üí write consolidated notes.
	- Finish Mini-Project:
	  
	   ‚úÖ ‚ÄúLinux Notes Repo‚Äù ‚Üí 30 commands + screenshots + explanations.
	  
	   ‚úÖ Push to GitHub.
- Practice Drill: Solve first 5 levels of OverTheWire Bandit.
- Mock Interview:
	- Explain Linux filesystem hierarchy.
	- How do you check which process is using port 8080?

‚ö° At the end of Week 1 (Day 7):
‚úÖ You‚Äôll know Linux filesystem, file ops, permissions, processes, search, and links.
‚úÖ You‚Äôll have a GitHub repo (Linux Notes Repo) ‚Üí your first portfolio project.
‚úÖ You‚Äôll be ready for real interview-style Linux basics Qs.



üìÖ Week 2: Linux Administration (Daily Roadmap)

Day 1 ‚Üí Users & Groups
- Topics:
	- useradd, usermod, passwd, deluser
	- Groups: groupadd, groups, /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow
	- Sudoers file ‚Üí visudo
	- User permissions best practices
- Practice:
	- Create 2 users (dev, tester) with different groups.
	- Give dev sudo rights but restrict tester.
- Mini-Project: Document ‚ÄúUser Management Cheatsheet‚Äù (commands + config file snippets).
- Interview Qs:
	- What‚Äôs in /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow?
	- Difference between root user and sudo?

Day 2 ‚Üí Process Management
- Topics:
	- View processes: ps, top, htop
	- Foreground vs background: fg, bg, jobs, &
	- Kill processes: kill, killall, signals (SIGTERM, SIGKILL)
	- Priorities: nice, renice
- Practice:
	- Run a script in background and monitor it.
	- Change process priority.
- Mini-Project: Write troubleshooting notes: ‚ÄúHow to handle stuck processes‚Äù.
- Interview Qs:
	- What‚Äôs the difference between kill -9 and kill -15?
	- How do you restart a stuck service?

Day 3 ‚Üí Services & Daemons
- Topics:
	- Init systems ‚Üí SysV vs Systemd
	- Managing services: systemctl start/stop/enable/status
	- Checking boot targets: systemctl get-default
	- Understanding runlevels
- Practice:
	- Enable Apache/NGINX service at boot.
	- Check logs of a failing service.
- Mini-Project: Create ‚ÄúLinux Service Runbook‚Äù ‚Üí start/stop/enable common services.
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between systemctl start and systemctl enable?
	- How do you check if a service failed at boot?

Day 4 ‚Üí Resource Monitoring
- Topics:
	- Disk usage: df, du, inodes
	- Memory: free -m, vmstat
	- CPU: uptime, iostat, sar
	- Load average interpretation
- Practice:
	- Monitor memory usage while running stress test (stress command if available).
	- Find top 5 processes using CPU/memory.
- Mini-Project: Build ‚ÄúLinux Monitoring Notes‚Äù ‚Üí explain load average with examples.
- Interview Qs:
	- What does load average: 3.5 mean?
	- How do you check which process is consuming disk space?

Day 5 ‚Üí Logs
- Topics:
	- Syslog basics ‚Üí /var/log/messages, /var/log/syslog
	- Systemd logs ‚Üí journalctl
	- Application logs vs system logs
	- Log rotation basics (/etc/logrotate.conf)
- Practice:
	- View last 50 lines of syslog.
	- Filter logs by service name using journalctl -u sshd.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúLinux Logging Guide‚Äù ‚Üí list of important log files and their purpose.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you check SSH login attempts?
	- Where do you find kernel logs?

Day 6 ‚Üí Package Management
- Topics:
	- Debian-based: apt, dpkg
	- RHEL-based: yum, dnf, rpm
	- Adding/removing repositories
	- Updating vs upgrading
- Practice:
	- Install Apache on Ubuntu and Nginx on CentOS.
	- Verify package version.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúLinux Package Manager Cheatsheet‚Äù (APT vs YUM commands side by side).
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between apt-get update and apt-get upgrade?
	- How do you rollback a package version?

Day 7 ‚Üí Archiving & Compression
- Topics:
	- tar, gzip, bzip2, xz, zip, unzip
	- Extracting archives
	- Combining compression + archiving
- Practice:
	- Create tar archive of /etc and compress it.
	- Extract it to a new folder.
- Mini-Project: Write script to back up /var/log into compressed archive daily.
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between tar and zip?
	- How do you compress while preserving file permissions?

‚ö° End of Week 2 Deliverables
- 3 mini-guides: User Management, Service Runbook, Logging Guide.
- 1 automation script for log backup.
- Notes on troubleshooting high CPU/memory/disk usage.
- Solid understanding of Linux admin tasks ‚Üí enough to manage AWS EC2/K8s nodes.

üìÖ Week 3: Git & Version Control (Daily Roadmap)

Day 1 ‚Üí Git Fundamentals
- Topics:
	- What is VCS (Version Control System)?
	- Git architecture: working directory, staging area, commit history.
	- Commands: git init, git clone, git status, git add, git commit.
	- Config basics: git config --global.
- Practice:
	- Initialize repo locally.
	- Make a couple of commits.
	- Check history with git log.
- Mini-Project: Create a repo called Git-Playground ‚Üí add a text file, track changes with commits.
- Interview Qs:
	- What‚Äôs the difference between git add and git commit?
	- Where does Git store commits?

Day 2 ‚Üí Branching & Merging
- Topics:
	- Branch concepts: HEAD, master/main, feature branches.
	- Commands: git branch, git checkout, git switch, git merge.
	- Fast-forward vs 3-way merge.
- Practice:
	- Create feature-1 branch.
	- Make changes ‚Üí merge into main.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúBranch Demo Repo‚Äù ‚Üí Create a repo with at least 2 branches and merge workflows.
- Interview Qs:
	- What‚Äôs the difference between fast-forward merge and recursive merge?
	- When would you create a new branch?

Day 3 ‚Üí Rebasing & History Management
- Topics:
	- Rebase basics: git rebase vs git merge.
	- Interactive rebase: git rebase -i.
	- Amending commits: git commit --amend.
	- Cleaning history: git reset, git revert, git stash.
- Practice:
	- Rebase feature branch on main.
	- Use interactive rebase to squash commits.
	- Try reverting a commit.
- Mini-Project: Create ‚ÄúRebase Practice Repo‚Äù ‚Üí demonstrate merge vs rebase.
- Interview Qs:
	- Merge vs rebase ‚Äì which do you prefer and why?
	- Difference between reset, revert, and checkout?

Day 4 ‚Üí GitHub Workflows
- Topics:
	- Remote repositories: git remote add, git push, git pull, git fetch.
	- Forking and Pull Requests (PRs).
	- Code review process.
	- GitHub Actions (intro only, deeper in CI/CD phase).
- Practice:
	- Push repo to GitHub.
	- Fork repo from another account ‚Üí make PR.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúDevOps-Playground Repo‚Äù ‚Üí Hosted on GitHub with clean commits and at least 1 PR merged.
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between git fetch and git pull?
	- What‚Äôs a fork vs a branch?

Day 5 ‚Üí Conflict Resolution
- Topics:
	- Why conflicts happen.
	- Conflict markers (<<<<, ====, >>>>).
	- Resolving conflicts in CLI and IDE (VS Code).
- Practice:
	- Simulate merge conflict by editing same file in two branches.
	- Resolve manually.
- Mini-Project: Add ‚ÄúConflict Resolution Notes‚Äù in your Git repo.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you handle merge conflicts?
	- How do you avoid frequent conflicts in teams?

Day 6 ‚Üí Tags, Releases & Semantic Versioning
- Topics:
	- Lightweight tags vs annotated tags.
	- git tag and git push --tags.
	- GitHub releases.
	- Semantic Versioning (v1.0.0 ‚Üí MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH).
- Practice:
	- Tag repo version v1.0.0.
	- Push to GitHub and create release.
- Mini-Project: Add a release to DevOps-Playground Repo with proper tag and changelog.
- Interview Qs:
	- What‚Äôs the difference between annotated and lightweight tags?
	- Why use semantic versioning?

Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up & Project
- Capstone Project:
  
   Create a real GitHub repo with:
	- At least 2 branches (feature + main).
	- Clean commit history (use rebase/squash).
	- Conflict resolution example.
	- 1 PR merged.
	- Version v1.0.0 release.
	- A README explaining your Git workflow.
- Deliverable: Link to polished GitHub repo.
- Interview Qs:
	- Walk me through your GitHub workflow.
	- How do you manage Git workflow in a team with 5+ developers?

‚ö° End of Week 3 Deliverables
- 2‚Äì3 Git repos: playground, rebase demo, polished DevOps repo.
- Hands-on knowledge of branching, merging, rebasing, tags, releases.
- Confidence with GitHub workflows ‚Üí PRs, forks, versioning.
- Ready to start Bash scripting (Week 4).

This week is critical because scripting = automation. Even basic shell scripts can save hours of manual work ‚Üí recruiters expect you to know this.
By the end of this week, you‚Äôll have a repo of automation scripts ‚Üí exactly what hiring managers love to see.

üìÖ Week 4: Bash Scripting (Daily Roadmap)

Day 1 ‚Üí Scripting Fundamentals
- Topics:
	- Writing your first script (#!/bin/bash).
	- Making scripts executable (chmod +x script.sh).
	- Variables ‚Üí defining, referencing ($VAR), command substitution ($(date)).
	- Quoting: single ', double ", backticks ``.
- Practice:
	- Script to print today‚Äôs date and current user.
	- Store output of ls into a variable and print.
- Mini-Project: hello.sh ‚Üí simple script printing system info (date, whoami, hostname).
- Interview Qs:
	- What does #!/bin/bash mean?
	- Difference between single and double quotes in Bash?

Day 2 ‚Üí Conditionals & Loops
- Topics:
	- if, elif, else conditions.
	- Numeric vs string comparisons (-eq, -lt, =, !=).
	- for, while, until loops.
	- case statement.
- Practice:
	- Write script to check if a file exists.
	- Loop through files in /etc and print names.
- Mini-Project: disk_check.sh ‚Üí alerts if disk usage > 80%.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you compare numbers in Bash?
	- Difference between for and while loops?

Day 3 ‚Üí Functions & Error Handling
- Topics:
	- Functions (function my_func {}).
	- Return codes & $?.
	- exit, trap, set -e, set -x.
	- Error handling best practices.
- Practice:
	- Function that checks if a service is running.
	- Add error handling to disk_check.sh.
- Mini-Project: service_check.sh ‚Üí function that checks if nginx is active, restart if not.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you capture exit status of a command?
	- What‚Äôs the use of set -e in scripts?

Day 4 ‚Üí File Handling & User Input
- Topics:
	- Reading files line by line (while read).
	- Redirects: >, >>, 2>.
	- Taking user input (read).
	- Working with arguments ($1, $@, $#).
- Practice:
	- Script that takes filename as input and prints number of lines.
	- Script that reads a list of users from file and adds them to system.
- Mini-Project: user_add.sh ‚Üí automate bulk user creation.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you handle command-line arguments in Bash?
	- How do you append vs overwrite output in a file?

Day 5 ‚Üí Automation & Scheduling
- Topics:
	- Cron jobs (crontab -e).
	- Automating backups with tar + cron.
	- Log rotation basics.
	- Combining Bash with systemctl and journalctl.
- Practice:
	- Create cron job to run disk_check.sh every 10 minutes.
	- Backup /var/log daily to /backup/logs.tar.gz.
- Mini-Project: backup.sh + cron job ‚Üí automated log backup.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you schedule a script to run daily?
	- Difference between cron and at?

Day 6 ‚Üí Debugging & Best Practices
- Topics:
	- Debugging with set -x.
	- Strict mode: set -euo pipefail.
	- Using ShellCheck to lint scripts.
	- Writing reusable scripts with arguments and functions.
- Practice:
	- Debug a failing script with set -x.
	- Run shellcheck on your scripts.
- Mini-Project: Refactor disk_check.sh ‚Üí add logging, error handling, and parameters.
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you debug a failing script?
	- Why use set -euo pipefail?

Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up & Project
- Capstone Project:
  
   Create a Linux Automation Scripts Repo with:
	- disk_check.sh ‚Üí Disk usage monitoring.
	- user_add.sh ‚Üí Bulk user creation.
	- backup.sh ‚Üí Automated log backup.
	- service_check.sh ‚Üí Monitor and restart service if down.
- Deliverables:
	- GitHub repo with scripts, README, and usage instructions.
- Interview Qs:
	- Walk me through one automation script you wrote.
	- How do you make Bash scripts more secure and reliable?

‚ö° End of Week 4 Deliverables
- 3‚Äì4 working automation scripts.
- Cron jobs + error handling in Bash.
- A polished GitHub repo ‚Üí ‚ÄúLinux Automation Scripts‚Äù.
- Confidence in Bash scripting for real DevOps tasks.


This week is all about core networking fundamentals + troubleshooting skills. Even as a DevSecOps fresher, interviewers love to throw network-related questions ‚Äî so this is must-have confidence zone.
By the end of this week, you‚Äôll have a Network Debug Guide repo with practical commands + troubleshooting playbooks.

üìÖ Week 5: Networking Basics (Daily Roadmap)

Day 1 ‚Üí Networking Fundamentals
- Topics:
	- OSI Model (7 layers) vs TCP/IP (4 layers).
	- Data flow: Application ‚Üí Transport ‚Üí Network ‚Üí Data Link ‚Üí Physical.
	- Encapsulation & packet structure.
	- Common protocols: HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SSH, SMTP.
- Practice:
	- Write down OSI model with real-world examples (e.g., DNS ‚Üí Application, IP ‚Üí Network).
	- Use curl -v to check an HTTP vs HTTPS response.
- Mini-Project: Create a diagram of OSI model with 2‚Äì3 protocol examples per layer.
- Interview Qs:
	- Explain OSI vs TCP/IP.
	- What protocol does DNS use (TCP/UDP)?

Day 2 ‚Üí IP Addressing & Subnetting
- Topics:
	- IPv4 basics: classes (A, B, C).
	- CIDR notation (/24, /16).
	- Private vs Public IPs.
	- Subnetting basics ‚Üí dividing networks.
- Practice:
	- Use ip addr or ifconfig to check local IP.
	- Calculate subnet for 192.168.1.0/24 ‚Üí How many hosts?
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúSubnet Calculator Script‚Äù in Python/Bash (simple).
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between private and public IP?
	- What is CIDR?

Day 3 ‚Üí DNS & DHCP
- Topics:
	- How DNS works: query ‚Üí recursive resolver ‚Üí root ‚Üí TLD ‚Üí authoritative server.
	- Records: A, AAAA, CNAME, MX, TXT, NS.
	- DHCP basics: how IPs are assigned automatically.
- Practice:
	- Use dig and nslookup to resolve google.com.
	- Run tcpdump -i any port 53 while resolving DNS.
- Mini-Project: Write ‚ÄúDNS Debug Notes‚Äù ‚Üí common DNS issues + fixes.
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between CNAME and A record?
	- How does DHCP assign IP addresses?

Day 4 ‚Üí Routing, ARP & Tools
- Topics:
	- Routing basics: default gateway, static vs dynamic routes.
	- ARP (Address Resolution Protocol).
	- Tools: ping, traceroute, ss, netstat, nc (netcat).
- Practice:
	- Use traceroute to check hops to google.com.
	- Use arp -a to see ARP cache.
	- Use nc -zv to test if a port is open.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúNetwork Tools Cheatsheet‚Äù repo ‚Üí commands + examples.
- Interview Qs:
	- What is ARP?
	- How do you check if a port is open?

Day 5 ‚Üí Firewalls & SSL/TLS Basics
- Topics:
	- Firewalls: iptables, nftables, ufw.
	- Stateful vs stateless firewalls.
	- TLS/SSL basics: handshake, certificates, CA.
- Practice:
	- Use ufw to block port 80, then test with curl.
	- Run openssl s_client -connect google.com:443 ‚Üí view TLS handshake.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúSSL Debug Guide‚Äù ‚Üí steps to check expired certificates.
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between firewall rules and security groups?
	- How does TLS handshake work?

Day 6 ‚Üí End-to-End Troubleshooting
- Topics:
	- Step-by-step debugging: Is host alive? Is DNS resolving? Is port open? Is service responding?
	- Common issues: DNS failure, packet loss, firewall blocking.
- Practice:
	- Simulate: stop DNS (systemctl stop systemd-resolved) ‚Üí debug.
	- Simulate: block port with ufw ‚Üí debug with curl.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúNetwork Debug Guide‚Äù ‚Üí 3 case studies (DNS issue, TLS expiry, firewall block).
- Interview Qs:
	- How do you debug a server that is not reachable?
	- Difference between TCP 3-way handshake and UDP?

Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up & Lab
- Capstone Lab:
  
   Set up a mini client-server app:
	- Python simple HTTP server (python3 -m http.server 8080).
	- Client uses curl/wget to connect.
	- Debug with ping, nc, tcpdump if client can‚Äôt reach server.
- Deliverables:
	- ‚ÄúNetwork Debug Guide‚Äù repo with commands, notes, diagrams.
- Interview Qs:
	- Walk me through how you debug a failed curl request.
	- How would you secure DNS?

‚ö° End of Week 5 Deliverables
- Repo: Network Debug Guide with playbooks.
- Mini projects: Subnet calculator, SSL debug notes, network tools cheatsheet.
- Confidence in core networking tools + troubleshooting.

This week builds directly on Week 5 (networking basics) but inside AWS ‚Äî VPC, subnets, SG vs NACLs, routing, and connectivity. These are core AWS interview topics and also the foundation for Terraform, Kubernetes, and DevSecOps labs later.
By the end of this week, you‚Äôll have a VPC Lab Project repo with diagrams + Terraform/CLI configs.

üìÖ Week 6: AWS Networking (Daily Roadmap)

Day 1 ‚Üí VPC Fundamentals
- Topics:
	- What is a VPC? (AWS Virtual Private Cloud).
	- CIDR notation for VPCs (10.0.0.0/16, /24).
	- Subnets: public vs private.
	- Default VPC vs custom VPC.
- Practice:
	- In AWS Free Tier, create a custom VPC (10.0.0.0/16).
	- Add one public subnet and one private subnet.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúMy First VPC‚Äù ‚Üí Diagram + screenshots of custom VPC.
- Interview Qs:
	- What‚Äôs the difference between public and private subnets?
	- Why do we need custom VPC instead of default?

Day 2 ‚Üí Routing & Internet Gateway
- Topics:
	- Route Tables: default routes, local routes.
	- Internet Gateway (IGW).
	- NAT Gateway basics (for private subnet internet access).
- Practice:
	- Attach IGW to VPC.
	- Create route in public subnet (0.0.0.0/0 ‚Üí IGW).
- Mini-Project: Add EC2 in public subnet ‚Üí verify it has internet access.
- Interview Qs:
	- How does a private EC2 access the internet?
	- Difference between IGW and NAT Gateway?

Day 3 ‚Üí Security Groups vs NACLs
- Topics:
	- Security Groups (SG): stateful, instance-level.
	- Network ACLs (NACLs): stateless, subnet-level.
	- Common rules: SSH (22), HTTP (80), HTTPS (443).
- Practice:
	- Create SG allowing only SSH from your IP.
	- Create NACL rule to deny all inbound HTTP.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúSG vs NACL Demo‚Äù ‚Üí doc with test cases (curl works with SG but blocked by NACL).
- Interview Qs:
	- Difference between SG and NACL?
	- Why are SGs stateful?

Day 4 ‚Üí Bastion Host & Private Subnet Access
- Topics:
	- Bastion host (jumpbox) ‚Üí SSH into private subnet EC2.
	- Key pairs & SSH.
	- Elastic IP (EIP).
- Practice:
	- Create Bastion host in public subnet.
	- Connect to private EC2 through Bastion (ssh -J).
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúPrivate Subnet Access Lab‚Äù ‚Üí step-by-step doc + diagram.
- Interview Qs:
	- Why do we use Bastion host?
	- How do you secure SSH access in AWS?

Day 5 ‚Üí VPC Peering & DNS in AWS
- Topics:
	- VPC Peering (connecting two VPCs).
	- Route53 basics: public vs private hosted zones.
	- Internal DNS resolution in AWS.
- Practice:
	- Create two VPCs and peer them.
	- Test connectivity using ping/curl between VPCs.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúVPC Peering Notes‚Äù ‚Üí screenshots of route tables + ping results.
- Interview Qs:
	- What is VPC Peering?
	- When to use Private Hosted Zones?

Day 6 ‚Üí Hands-On Troubleshooting
- Topics:
	- Common VPC issues:
		- EC2 in private subnet can‚Äôt reach internet ‚Üí missing NAT Gateway.
		- EC2 can‚Äôt be reached ‚Üí SG/NACL issue.
		- DNS resolution fails ‚Üí Route53 misconfig.
- Practice:
	- Break routes and SG rules intentionally ‚Üí debug.
	- Use ping, curl, and VPC flow logs.
- Mini-Project: ‚ÄúVPC Debug Guide‚Äù ‚Üí document 3 failures + fixes.
- Interview Qs:
	- EC2 in private subnet not connecting to internet ‚Äî what steps do you check?
	- How do you debug SG vs NACL issues?

Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up & Lab
- Capstone Lab: Build a 2-tier AWS VPC setup:
	- VPC with 1 public subnet + 1 private subnet.
	- Bastion host in public subnet.
	- Private EC2 with S3 access (via IAM role).
	- NAT Gateway for internet access.
- Deliverables:
	- GitHub repo: Terraform/CLI configs + diagram + README.
- Interview Qs:
	- Walk me through your VPC project.
	- What are security concerns in this architecture?

‚ö° End of Week 6 Deliverables
- Repo: VPC Lab Project with diagrams & configs.
- Mini-projects: SG vs NACL demo, Bastion host setup, VPC debug guide.
- Confidence in AWS networking ‚Äî foundation for Kubernetes clusters, CI/CD infra, and DevSecOps later.

Week 7 (Python Basics) ‚Äî this is where you‚Äôll start coding properly. Since you‚Äôre aiming to reach 2 years exp level, I‚Äôll expand it with full syllabus coverage + daily breakdown (the same detail as Linux/Git weeks).

üìÖ Week 7: Python Basics (5 Days)
üéØ Goal
- Build strong programming fundamentals in Python.
- Learn data structures, control flow, functions, and error handling.
- Be able to write small automation scripts (log parsers, calculators, etc.).

Day 1 ‚Üí Python Setup & Syntax Essentials
Topics:
- Install Python (3.10+).
- Python interpreter vs script execution.
- Variables, dynamic typing, naming rules.
- Data types: int, float, str, bool.
- Input/output: input(), print().
- String basics: slicing, concatenation, f-strings, escape sequences.
Practice:
- Write ‚ÄúHello, World!‚Äù script.
- Input user name ‚Üí print greeting.
- Do string slicing (reverse string, substring extraction).
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è string_play.py: Take a sentence and print: word count, reversed sentence, all uppercase/lowercase.
Interview Qs:
- What is dynamic typing in Python?
- How do you reverse a string in Python?

Day 2 ‚Üí Conditionals & Loops
Topics:
- Indentation in Python (no {} braces).
- Conditionals: if, elif, else.
- Comparison operators, logical operators.
- Loops: for, while, break, continue.
- Iterating over lists/strings.
- Range function.
Practice:
- Write program: Check if number is prime.
- Loop through list of numbers ‚Üí print even/odd.
- Multiplication table using for.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è prime_numbers.py: Print all prime numbers between 1‚Äì100.
Interview Qs:
- Difference between break and continue.
- How do you loop through both index and value in Python?

Day 3 ‚Üí Data Structures (Lists, Tuples, Sets, Dicts)
Topics:
- Lists: indexing, slicing, append, extend, insert, remove, pop, sort.
- Tuples: immutability, tuple packing/unpacking.
- Sets: unique elements, set operations (union, intersection, difference).
- Dictionaries: key-value pairs, adding/updating/removing items, iteration.
- len(), type(), in keyword.
Practice:
- Create dictionary of student ‚Üí name, age, grade. Print keys & values.
- Write program to remove duplicates from a list using set().
- Count frequency of words in a sentence using dictionary.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è word_counter.py: Read a paragraph ‚Üí output word count frequency as dictionary.
Interview Qs:
- Difference between list and tuple?
- When to use set vs list?

Day 4 ‚Üí Functions & Modules
Topics:
- Defining functions with def.
- Parameters: positional, default, keyword, *args, **kwargs.
- Return values.
- Scope: local vs global.
- Importing built-in modules (math, random, datetime).
- Creating your own module (separate .py file).
Practice:
- Function to calculate factorial of a number.
- Function to return max of 3 numbers.
- Import math ‚Üí use sqrt, pow, ceil, floor.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è calculator.py: Build simple calculator using functions (add, subtract, multiply, divide).
Interview Qs:
- What is the difference between *args and **kwargs?
- Explain scope of variables in Python.

Day 5 ‚Üí Exception Handling & File Handling
Topics:
- Errors vs exceptions.
- Try, except, finally.
- Raising exceptions with raise.
- File handling: open(), read, write, append.
- Context managers (with open() as f:).
- Common exceptions: ValueError, KeyError, IOError.
Practice:
- Try to divide by zero ‚Üí handle with exception.
- Open a file ‚Üí write lines ‚Üí read lines back.
- Program: check if file exists before reading.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è log_reader.py: Open a log file, count number of error lines, handle missing file gracefully.
Interview Qs:
- Difference between try-except and try-finally.
- How do you safely open and close a file in Python?

‚úÖ End of Week 7 Deliverables:
- 4‚Äì5 scripts in GitHub repo (string_play.py, prime_numbers.py, word_counter.py, calculator.py, log_reader.py).
- Markdown cheatsheet ‚Üí Python basics (syntax, loops, data structures, exceptions).
- Confidence in basic scripting for automation.

Week 8 (AWS Networking Intro) with the same daily-level detail.
This week is critical ‚Äî if Linux was the ‚ÄúOS foundation‚Äù, AWS networking (VPC, subnets, routing, SGs, NACLs) is the cloud foundation for everything you‚Äôll build later.

üìÖ Week 8: AWS Networking Intro (5 Days)
üéØ Goal
- Understand AWS VPC networking inside-out.
- Be able to set up secure networks (public/private subnets, route tables, SGs, NACLs).
- Gain confidence in troubleshooting networking issues in AWS.

Day 1 ‚Üí VPC & Subnets
Topics:
- What is a VPC? Default VPC vs custom VPC.
- CIDR notation (10.0.0.0/16, 10.0.1.0/24).
- Public vs private subnets.
- Subnet association with route tables.
- Availability Zones (AZs).
- Elastic IP basics.
Practice:
- Create a custom VPC (10.0.0.0/16).
- Create 2 subnets: one public (10.0.1.0/24), one private (10.0.2.0/24).
- Attach Internet Gateway to VPC.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è ‚ÄúCustom VPC Setup‚Äù ‚Üí Diagram + Terraform/CLI code for VPC with 2 subnets.
Interview Qs:
- What is the difference between public and private subnet?
- Why do we use CIDR in networking?

Day 2 ‚Üí Routing & Gateways
Topics:
- Route tables: main vs custom route table.
- Internet Gateway vs NAT Gateway.
- Public subnet = route to IGW.
- Private subnet = route to NAT GW.
- Bastion host / jumpbox concept.
- Elastic IP association.
Practice:
- Configure route tables:
	- Public subnet ‚Üí IGW.
	- Private subnet ‚Üí NAT GW (in public subnet).
- Launch EC2 in private subnet ‚Üí access internet via NAT.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è ‚ÄúPrivate EC2 Internet Access‚Äù ‚Üí Document setup of NAT Gateway + private EC2 accessing updates.
Interview Qs:
- What is the difference between NAT GW and IGW?
- How does a private EC2 reach the internet?

Day 3 ‚Üí Security Groups (SGs) & NACLs
Topics:
- Security Group (SG): stateful firewall at instance level.
- Network ACL (NACL): stateless firewall at subnet level.
- SG rules (inbound/outbound).
- NACL rules (numbered rules, allow/deny).
- Common patterns:
	- Web server (80, 443 inbound).
	- SSH (22 inbound restricted to office IP).
Practice:
- Create SG for web app: allow 80/443 from anywhere, 22 from your IP.
- Create NACL for private subnet: deny all inbound except port 3306 (MySQL).
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è ‚ÄúSG vs NACL Demo‚Äù ‚Üí EC2 in public subnet ‚Üí test ping, SSH, HTTP with different SG/NACL configs.
Interview Qs:
- SG vs NACL? Stateful vs stateless?
- Can an EC2 belong to multiple SGs?

Day 4 ‚Üí VPC Peering & DNS
Topics:
- VPC Peering: connecting 2 VPCs.
- Limitations of peering (no transitive peering).
- Route53 basics: hosted zones, record types (A, CNAME, MX).
- Private hosted zones (DNS inside VPC).
- Public hosted zones (internet-facing).
Practice:
- Create 2 VPCs ‚Üí peer them.
- Update route tables ‚Üí allow cross-VPC communication.
- Create Route53 hosted zone ‚Üí map domain to EC2 public IP.
Mini-Project:
‚û°Ô∏è ‚ÄúVPC Peering Setup‚Äù ‚Üí 2 VPCs (10.0.0.0/16, 10.1.0.0/16) ‚Üí communicate via peering.
Interview Qs:
- What are limitations of VPC peering?
- How does Route53 resolve DNS?

Day 5 ‚Üí Wrap-up + Mini-Capstone
Capstone Project:
‚û°Ô∏è ‚ÄúAWS Secure Networking Project‚Äù
- Create VPC (10.0.0.0/16).
- Public subnet with IGW + Bastion host.
- Private subnet with EC2 (only reachable via Bastion).
- NAT Gateway for private EC2 internet.
- SG + NACL rules.
- Route53 record ‚Üí public domain ‚Üí Bastion.
Deliverables:
- Diagram of architecture (draw.io / Lucidchart).
- Terraform/CLI/Console setup steps.
- README with risks & best practices.
Interview Qs:
- How do you design a secure 2-tier app in AWS networking?
- Why should SSH not be exposed directly to public EC2?

‚úÖ End of Week 8 Deliverables:
- 3 small repos/demos (Custom VPC, SG vs NACL, VPC Peering).
- 1 mini-capstone (AWS Secure Networking Project).
- Clear understanding of AWS networking ‚Üí critical for troubleshooting later in CI/CD & K8s.


