Week 26 is one of the most critical weeks in the roadmap ‚Üí Kubernetes Security.
This is the turning point where you go beyond just ‚Äúdeploying apps‚Äù ‚Üí to actually hardening clusters.
Recruiters & interviewers love asking K8s security questions (RBAC, Secrets, PSPs/Pod Security Standards, Network Policies).
If you nail this week, you‚Äôll be way above fresher level.

üìÖ Week 26: Kubernetes Security Foundations
üéØ Goal
- Master Pod Security Standards, RBAC, and Network Policies.
- Learn how to protect K8s Secrets, Service Accounts, and Admission Controllers.
- Deploy secure workloads and practice real-world security scenarios.
- Build a Kubernetes Security Demo Project repo.

üîπ Day 1 ‚Üí Pod Security Standards (PSS)
Topics
- Pod Security Admission (baseline, restricted policies).
- Legacy PodSecurityPolicies (deprecated, but still asked in interviews).
- Restricting privileged containers.
- Blocking hostNetwork, hostPID, and root users.
Practice
- Apply baseline Pod Security to dev namespace.
- Apply restricted Pod Security to prod namespace.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-pod-security-demo/ ‚Üí namespace with PodSecurity restricted ‚Üí test deploying privileged vs non-privileged pod.
Interview Qs
- What are Pod Security Standards in Kubernetes?
- How do you prevent privileged containers from running?

üîπ Day 2 ‚Üí Kubernetes RBAC (Advanced)
Topics
- Recap: Roles, ClusterRoles, RoleBindings, ClusterRoleBindings.
- Least privilege principle ‚Üí only give required permissions.
- Service Accounts for Pods.
- Binding ServiceAccounts to workloads.
Practice
- Create Role ‚Üí allow read-only pods.
- Bind Role to ServiceAccount.
- Deploy pod ‚Üí test access with token.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-rbac-security-demo/ ‚Üí ServiceAccount bound to pod with read-only access to K8s API.
Interview Qs
- Difference between Role and ClusterRole?
- How do ServiceAccounts secure pod-to-API communication?

üîπ Day 3 ‚Üí Kubernetes Secrets Management
Topics
- Storing secrets in K8s (base64 encoding vs encryption at rest).
- Mounting secrets ‚Üí env vars or volumes.
- External secret managers ‚Üí AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault.
- Avoiding hardcoded secrets in YAML.
Practice
- Create Secret ‚Üí db-password.
- Mount secret in Flask app ‚Üí access via env var.
- Integrate with AWS Secrets Manager using external-secrets operator.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-secrets-demo/ ‚Üí App deployment using AWS Secrets Manager + external-secrets operator.
Interview Qs
- How are K8s Secrets stored by default?
- How do you integrate external secret stores?

üîπ Day 4 ‚Üí Network Policies
Topics
- Why network policies? ‚Üí zero trust networking inside cluster.
- Default allow-all vs default deny.
- Allowing traffic between namespaces.
- Allowing pod-to-pod communication selectively.
Practice
- Deploy frontend + backend pods.
- Create NetworkPolicy ‚Üí frontend can talk to backend, but not DB.
- Create deny-all policy for prod namespace.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-networkpolicy-demo/ ‚Üí YAMLs for frontend-backend DB traffic isolation.
Interview Qs
- What‚Äôs the difference between Security Groups (AWS) and Network Policies (K8s)?
- How do you implement zero trust networking inside Kubernetes?

üîπ Day 5 ‚Üí Admission Controllers & Policy Enforcement
Topics
- What are Admission Controllers? (Mutating vs Validating).
- Open Policy Agent (OPA) + Gatekeeper.
- Example policies:
	- No privileged pods.
	- Enforce labels on all resources.
	- Enforce resource limits.
Practice
- Install Gatekeeper.
- Write OPA policy ‚Üí deny pods without resource limits.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-opa-policies/ ‚Üí Repo with 2‚Äì3 Gatekeeper policies (deny privileged pods, enforce labels).
Interview Qs
- What‚Äôs the role of Admission Controllers in Kubernetes?
- How do OPA/Gatekeeper enforce policies?

üîπ Day 6 ‚Üí Capstone Project: Secure Kubernetes Setup
Project ‚Üí ‚ÄúKubernetes Security Pack‚Äù
- Namespace isolation with Pod Security Standards.
- RBAC setup ‚Üí read-only vs admin roles.
- Secrets managed via AWS Secrets Manager.
- Network Policies ‚Üí frontend-backend-DB isolation.
- Gatekeeper OPA ‚Üí enforce no-privileged pods + mandatory labels.
Deliverables
- Repo: k8s-security-pack/.
- YAMLs for RBAC, NetworkPolicies, Secrets, OPA policies.
- README with explanation + diagrams.
Interview Drill
- Walk me through how you secured your Kubernetes cluster.
- How do you handle secrets securely in K8s?
- What happens if you apply a deny-all NetworkPolicy?

üîπ Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up + Mock Interview
Tasks
- Push repos ‚Üí k8s-pod-security-demo, k8s-rbac-security-demo, k8s-secrets-demo, k8s-networkpolicy-demo, k8s-opa-policies, k8s-security-pack.
- Write blog ‚Üí ‚ÄúHow I Secured My Kubernetes Cluster: RBAC, Secrets, Network Policies, OPA‚Äù.
Mock Interview
- How do you enforce least privilege in Kubernetes?
- Explain Pod Security Standards vs PodSecurityPolicies.
- How do you prevent pods from accessing external networks?

‚úÖ End of Week 26 Deliverables
- 5‚Äì6 repos ‚Üí PodSecurity, RBAC, Secrets, Network Policies, OPA.
- 1 capstone repo ‚Üí Kubernetes Security Pack.
- Confidence in K8s security interview questions (RBAC, secrets, network policies).
- Portfolio-ready ‚Üí you‚Äôll now stand out as a fresher with security-first mindset.

Week 27 is where we go deep into CI/CD Security.
By now, you‚Äôve built solid pipelines (Jenkins + Docker + Kubernetes). Now you‚Äôll secure them with secrets management, image scanning, dependency scanning, and pipeline hardening.
This is a huge differentiator in interviews ‚Üí most freshers know Jenkins basics, but very few know how to secure pipelines.

üìÖ Week 27: CI/CD Security (Daily Roadmap)
üéØ Goal
- Secure Jenkins pipelines ‚Üí no hardcoded secrets.
- Integrate HashiCorp Vault / AWS Secrets Manager with Jenkins.
- Add security scans ‚Üí Trivy (images), Snyk (dependencies), Checkov (IaC).
- Deliver a Secure CI/CD Pipeline Project Repo.

üîπ Day 1 ‚Üí Secrets Management in CI/CD
Topics
- Why hardcoded secrets are bad.
- Jenkins Credentials Manager.
- HashiCorp Vault ‚Üí dynamic secrets.
- AWS Secrets Manager integration.
Practice
- Store GitHub PAT + AWS keys in Jenkins Credentials.
- Inject into Jenkinsfile using withCredentials.
- Setup Vault ‚Üí fetch secrets during pipeline.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è secure-jenkins-secrets-demo/ ‚Üí Jenkins pipeline fetching DB password from Vault.
Interview Qs
- Why should secrets never be stored in Jenkinsfiles?
- How do Jenkins + Vault integrate?

üîπ Day 2 ‚Üí Docker Image Scanning (Trivy)
Topics
- Why image scanning matters (CVEs, supply chain security).
- Trivy basics ‚Üí scan Docker image.
- Jenkins pipeline integration ‚Üí fail build on critical CVEs.
Practice
- Scan flask-app:latest with Trivy.
- Add Trivy stage in Jenkinsfile.
- Fail pipeline if CVSS score ‚â• HIGH.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è jenkins-trivy-pipeline/ ‚Üí CI/CD pipeline with image scan + report artifact.
Interview Qs
- What types of vulnerabilities can Trivy detect?
- How do you enforce image scanning in CI/CD?

üîπ Day 3 ‚Üí Dependency Scanning (Snyk)
Topics
- Software Composition Analysis (SCA).
- Snyk for Python/Java/Node dependencies.
- Pipeline integration ‚Üí fail build if vulnerable dependencies.
Practice
- Install Snyk CLI.
- Run snyk test on requirements.txt / package.json.
- Add Jenkins pipeline stage ‚Üí publish results.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è jenkins-snyk-demo/ ‚Üí Jenkinsfile with dependency scan stage.
Interview Qs
- Difference between image scanning and dependency scanning?
- How does Snyk detect vulnerable libraries?

üîπ Day 4 ‚Üí Infrastructure as Code (IaC) Scanning
Topics
- IaC security risks (Terraform misconfigs, open security groups).
- Tools: Checkov, tfsec.
- Jenkins pipeline integration ‚Üí scan before apply.
Practice
- Run Checkov on terraform-aws-infra/.
- Detect security misconfigs (public S3 bucket, open SGs).
- Add pipeline stage ‚Üí fail on HIGH misconfigs.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è jenkins-iac-security/ ‚Üí Jenkinsfile with Checkov scan on Terraform code.
Interview Qs
- Why scan Terraform before apply?
- Difference between Checkov and Trivy?

üîπ Day 5 ‚Üí Pipeline Hardening
Topics
- Jenkins security best practices:
	- Run Jenkins with minimal plugins.
	- Restrict admin access.
	- Role-based access plugin.
	- Disable script approvals for unsafe Groovy.
- Secure pipeline practices:
	- Fail fast ‚Üí break on error.
	- Immutable builds ‚Üí no mutable artifacts.
	- Only signed images pushed.
Practice
- Enable Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) in Jenkins.
- Restrict access ‚Üí only CI/CD admins can modify jobs.
- Harden Jenkins agent nodes.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è jenkins-pipeline-hardening.md ‚Üí doc with 10 Jenkins hardening steps.
Interview Qs
- How do you secure Jenkins jobs?
- What‚Äôs the risk of using too many Jenkins plugins?

üîπ Day 6 ‚Üí Capstone: Secure CI/CD Pipeline
Project ‚Üí ‚ÄúSecure CI/CD Pipeline for Flask App‚Äù
- Jenkinsfile with stages:
	1. Checkout
	2. Build Docker image
	3. Scan image with Trivy
	4. Scan dependencies with Snyk
	5. Scan Terraform with Checkov
	6. Deploy to staging (K8s) only if scans pass
- Secrets ‚Üí pulled from Vault (DB password).
- Artifact reports ‚Üí archived in Jenkins.
Deliverables
- Repo: secure-ci-cd-pipeline/
- Jenkinsfile, Vault config, Trivy + Snyk reports.
- README with pipeline diagram.
Interview Drill
- Walk me through your Secure CI/CD pipeline.
- How do you enforce security scans before deployment?
- How do you handle secrets in Jenkins pipelines?

üîπ Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up + Mock Interview
Tasks
- Push repos ‚Üí secure-jenkins-secrets-demo, jenkins-trivy-pipeline, jenkins-snyk-demo, jenkins-iac-security, secure-ci-cd-pipeline.
- Write blog ‚Üí ‚ÄúHow I Secured My Jenkins CI/CD Pipeline with Vault, Trivy, Snyk, and Checkov‚Äù.
Mock Interview
- How do you secure Jenkins pipelines?
- Explain Trivy vs Snyk vs Checkov.
- What‚Äôs your approach if security scan fails in pipeline?

‚úÖ End of Week 27 Deliverables
- 4 mini-project repos ‚Üí secrets demo, Trivy, Snyk, IaC scan.
- 1 capstone repo ‚Üí Secure CI/CD Pipeline.
- Docs ‚Üí Jenkins pipeline hardening guide.
- You‚Äôll be able to explain and demonstrate DevSecOps pipelines ‚Äî a massive advantage in interviews.

Week 28 is where we step into Kubernetes Security (DevSecOps for K8s).
Up until now, you‚Äôve been deploying workloads on Kubernetes ‚Äî now you‚Äôll secure them with runtime security (Falco), compliance scanning (kube-bench), penetration testing (kube-hunter), and Pod Security Standards (PSS/PSA).
This is a real differentiator ‚Üí most candidates stop at K8s basics + Ingress. If you know K8s security tools, you‚Äôll look like an engineer with 2+ years hands-on exposure.

üìÖ Week 28: Kubernetes Security (Daily Roadmap)
üéØ Goal
- Learn and apply Kubernetes security practices.
- Use open-source security tools: Falco, Kube-Bench, Kube-Hunter.
- Understand Pod Security Standards (PSS) and Admission Controllers.
- Deliver a Secure Kubernetes Cluster Demo Project Repo.

üîπ Day 1 ‚Üí Kubernetes Security Basics
Topics
- Shared responsibility in Kubernetes security (cloud vs user).
- Attack surfaces ‚Üí API server, etcd, kubelet, Pods.
- Pod Security Standards (PSS ‚Üí Privileged, Baseline, Restricted).
- Admission Controllers overview.
Practice
- Enable PodSecurity admission in Minikube.
- Deploy pods with/without root privileges ‚Üí test enforcement.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-pod-security-demo/ ‚Üí YAML files showing restricted vs privileged pod configs.
Interview Qs
- What‚Äôs the difference between PSS levels?
- Why should containers not run as root?

üîπ Day 2 ‚Üí Falco (Runtime Security)
Topics
- Falco ‚Üí open-source runtime security tool.
- Detects suspicious activity:
	- Shell inside containers.
	- Writing to sensitive dirs.
	- Privilege escalation.
Practice
- Install Falco via Helm in Minikube.
- Trigger alerts:
	- Exec into pod (kubectl exec -it) ‚Üí Falco detects shell access.
	- Write file in /etc.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-falco-demo/ ‚Üí screenshots + logs of Falco detecting suspicious activity.
Interview Qs
- How does Falco detect runtime threats?
- What‚Äôs the role of eBPF in Falco?

üîπ Day 3 ‚Üí Kube-Bench (CIS Benchmark Compliance)
Topics
- CIS Kubernetes Benchmark ‚Üí security best practices.
- Kube-Bench ‚Üí automated CIS compliance checks.
- Checks API server, etcd, kubelet configs.
Practice
- Run Kube-Bench on Minikube.
- Review failed checks (e.g., API server without audit logs).
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-kube-bench-report/ ‚Üí store JSON/HTML scan report + remediation notes.
Interview Qs
- What does kube-bench check for?
- How do you remediate failed CIS controls?

üîπ Day 4 ‚Üí Kube-Hunter (Penetration Testing)
Topics
- Kube-Hunter ‚Üí simulates attacks on K8s clusters.
- Scans cluster externally (recon mode) and internally (active mode).
- Detects misconfigurations (open dashboard, unsecured API server).
Practice
- Run kube-hunter in Docker: docker run aquasec/kube-hunter.
- Perform external scan of Minikube.
- Analyze findings.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-kube-hunter-report/ ‚Üí repo with scan results + remediation steps.
