Week 42 üöÄ
By this stage, you‚Äôve covered Zero Trust, Kubernetes, Cloud Security, SIEM/SOAR, Container Security, and Compliance.
Now we‚Äôll enter Cloud Forensics & Incident Response (CFIR) ‚Äî a critical skill that very few DevOps/DevSecOps freshers ever touch.
This will differentiate you massively because you‚Äôll be able to say:
‚ÄúI not only built secure pipelines, but I can also detect, investigate, and respond to real cloud incidents.‚Äù

üìÖ Week 42: Cloud Forensics & Incident Response (CFIR)
üéØ Goal
- Learn how to investigate AWS/K8s incidents.
- Collect & analyze logs (CloudTrail, GuardDuty, Falco, Auditd).
- Perform memory/disk forensics on compromised workloads.
- Build an Incident Forensics Lab ‚Üí repo + runbook.

üîπ Day 1 ‚Üí Forensics & IR Foundations
Topics
- What is Cloud Forensics?
- NIST Incident Response lifecycle:
	1. Preparation
	2. Detection
	3. Containment
	4. Eradication
	5. Recovery
	6. Lessons Learned
- Key sources: Cloud logs, K8s audit logs, memory dumps.
Practice
- Create IR workflow diagram for AWS + K8s.
- Set up S3 ‚ÄúForensics Bucket‚Äù ‚Üí central log collection.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è ir-foundations/ ‚Üí IR workflow doc + AWS/K8s log sources mapping.
Interview Qs
- What are the phases of incident response?
- What‚Äôs the difference between forensics vs monitoring?

üîπ Day 2 ‚Üí AWS Forensics (CloudTrail + GuardDuty)
Topics
- CloudTrail log analysis ‚Üí detecting API misuse.
- GuardDuty findings ‚Üí crypto mining, IAM brute force.
- Using Athena for log queries.
Practice
- Simulate IAM brute force ‚Üí generate GuardDuty finding.
- Query CloudTrail ‚Üí detect suspicious IAM activity.
- Store logs in S3 bucket ‚Üí Athena queries.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è aws-ir-lab/ ‚Üí CloudTrail query scripts + GuardDuty findings analysis.
Interview Qs
- How do you detect a compromised IAM user?
- Difference between GuardDuty & CloudTrail?

üîπ Day 3 ‚Üí Kubernetes Forensics
Topics
- Collecting K8s audit logs.
- Detecting suspicious activity:
	- Privileged Pod deployed.
	- Unauthorized RBAC changes.
- Tools: kubectl logs, auditd, Falco.
Practice
- Deploy malicious Pod (privileged).
- Detect with audit logs + Falco alert.
- Export logs for analysis.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è k8s-ir-lab/ ‚Üí K8s audit + Falco alert analysis repo.
Interview Qs
- How do you detect privilege escalation in Kubernetes?
- What‚Äôs the role of audit logs in IR?

üîπ Day 4 ‚Üí Memory & Disk Forensics
Topics
- Memory forensics ‚Üí detect malicious processes.
- Disk forensics ‚Üí analyze compromised container/EC2.
- Tools: Volatility, LiME, Autopsy.
Practice
- Dump EC2 memory with LiME.
- Analyze memory dump with Volatility (list processes, connections).
- Mount Docker container filesystem ‚Üí analyze logs.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è forensics-lab/ ‚Üí Memory + disk forensics reports.
Interview Qs
- What is Volatility used for?
- How do you preserve evidence in cloud forensics?

üîπ Day 5 ‚Üí Incident Simulation & Playbook
Topics
- Simulating cloud attack ‚Üí compromised EC2 with crypto mining.
- Detection ‚Üí GuardDuty, CloudTrail, Falco.
- Playbook: Step-by-step IR actions.
Practice
- Create ‚ÄúCrypto Mining Incident‚Äù scenario.
- Respond: isolate EC2, snapshot disk, analyze logs, rotate IAM keys.
- Document IR steps in Markdown.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è incident-playbook/ ‚Üí Playbook repo for simulated AWS/K8s incidents.
Interview Qs
- Walk me through your incident playbook.
- How do you contain a compromised EC2?

üîπ Day 6 ‚Üí Capstone Project: Cloud Forensics & IR Lab
Project ‚Üí ‚ÄúCloud Incident Response Lab‚Äù
