Week 47 ‚Äî Purple Teaming & Detection Engineering (Red‚ÜîBlue integration)
üéØ Goal:
Bridge offense and defense: run adversary emulation, build/validate detections, tune SIEM/SOAR playbooks, and turn attack findings into robust detection rules and automated responses. By week‚Äôs end you‚Äôll be able to run a small Purple Team exercise, produce detection coverage mapped to MITRE ATT&CK, and deliver hardened detection rules + SOAR playbooks.

Day 1 ‚Äî Purple Team Foundations & Planning
Topics
- What is Purple Teaming vs Red/Blue in isolation.
- Objectives for a Purple Team: measurable detection coverage, reduce dwell time, improve playbooks.
- Detection engineering workflow: threat ‚Üí telemetry ‚Üí detection rule ‚Üí test ‚Üí tune ‚Üí onboard to SOAR.
Practice
- Choose 3 MITRE ATT&CK techniques (e.g., Credential Access: brute-force; Lateral Movement: SSH abuse; Exfiltration: S3 exfil).
- Create a Purple Team plan: success criteria, telemetry required (CloudTrail, K8s audit, Falco, ELK), timeframe.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è purple-plan/ ‚Äî YAML/Markdown: chosen ATT&CK techniques, telemetry mapping, detection acceptance criteria.
Interview Qs
- What‚Äôs a Purple Team and why is it valuable?
- How do you choose which techniques to prioritize?

Day 2 ‚Äî Telemetry Coverage & Data Engineering
Topics
- Telemetry sources and enrichment: logs, metrics, traces, process events, network flow.
- Log normalization, parsing, and enriching (add host, user, tags).
- Designing effective detections needs correct fields (user, src_ip, process, command_line, resource).
Practice
- Inventory your telemetry sources for the lab (CloudTrail, VPC Flow Logs, Falco, K8s audit, Sysmon-like events for Linux).
- Write or improve a Fluent Bit/Fluentd configuration to add fields and route security-relevant logs into ELK/Loki or your SIEM.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è telemetry-coverage/ ‚Äî Fluent Bit config + sample enriched logs and mapping doc.
Interview Qs
- Why is log enrichment important for detection accuracy?
- What fields are critical to detect lateral movement?

Day 3 ‚Äî Detection Engineering: Rules & Queries
Topics
- Detection rule patterns: anomaly-based, signature-based, multi-source correlation.
- Writing queries for SIEM (ELK/Kibana, Sigma translation concept).
- Avoiding false positives: thresholding, whitelisting, baseline.
Practice
- Implement 3 detection rules targeting Day 1 ATT&CK techniques:
	- Failed SSH attempts > threshold in short time (CloudTrail/VPC/host logs).
	- Unusual S3 GETs from atypical source IP (CloudTrail + Geo enrichment).
	- Suspicious process exec in containers (Falco rule).
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è detections/ ‚Äî Kibana queries + Sigma-style YAML of rules + test dataset to validate.
Interview Qs
- How do you prevent a detection from producing hundreds of false positives?
- What‚Äôs the difference between correlation rule and anomaly detection?

Day 4 ‚Äî Test & Validate (Purple Exercise #1)
Topics
- Running controlled adversary emulation against the lab.
- Capture telemetry for each attack step; evaluate detection coverage and time-to-detect.
- Logging, evidence capture, and labeling.
Practice
- Execute Atomic Red Team or Caldera scenarios for your 3 techniques.
- For each technique record: attack timeline, raw events, which detections fired (if any), and missed signals.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è purple-exercise-1/ ‚Äî attack scripts, execution timeline, detection results table (detected? time-to-detect? false positive count).
Interview Qs
- How do you measure detection effectiveness?
- What is Mean Time To Detect (MTTD) and why does it matter?

Day 5 ‚Äî Triage, Alert Tuning & SOAR Playbook Development
Topics
- Triage workflow: enrich alert, investigate, escalate.
- Building SOAR playbooks for automated response (isolate host, rotate keys, block IP).
- Playbook idempotency & safe actions.
Practice
- Create a SOAR playbook for one alert (e.g., S3 exfil alert): enrich (who, where), run quick checks (CloudTrail confirm, list recent object downloads), then automated action (revoke temporary credentials / quarantine S3 object / notify Slack).
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è soar-playbooks/ ‚Äî JSON/YAML playbook for Shuffle/TheHive/Cortex or pseudo-code if tool not available + tests for idempotency/safety.
Interview Qs
- What steps should an automated playbook include for suspected credential compromise?
- How do you avoid dangerous auto-remediations?

Day 6 ‚Äî Purple Exercise #2: Iterate, Harden & Document
Topics
- Re-run emulation, focusing on missed detection gaps from Day 4.
- Harden detection rules: add enrichment, cross-source correlation, adaptive thresholds.
- Document detection logic, tuning rationale, and create runbook entries for SOC analysts.
Practice
- Re-run attacks; confirm that tuned detections now catch them and that SOAR playbook responds as expected.
- Produce detection documentation with example alerts, required fields, false-positive examples, and triage steps.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è purple-exercise-2/ ‚Äî final attack runs, before/after detection coverage comparison, updated rule files, runbooks for SOC.
Interview Qs
- How do you document a detection to be handed to an analyst?
- How do you prioritize detections to implement first?

Day 7 ‚Äî Capstone: Purple Team Report + Handover
Deliverables
- purple-capstone/ repo containing:
	- purple-plan/, telemetry-coverage/, detections/, purple-exercise-1/, soar-playbooks/, purple-exercise-2/
	- A consolidated Purple Team Report: MITRE ATT&CK mapping matrix, detection coverage heatmap, MTTD improvements, residual gaps and next steps.
	- SOC Handover docs: playbooks, runbooks, false-positive tuning instructions.
Interview Drill
- Present the Purple Team findings: show one technique from attack ‚Üí detection ‚Üí playbook response.
- Explain a tuning decision you made and why it reduced false positives.
- How would you scale these detections across multiple teams/accounts?

‚úÖ End of Week 47 Deliverables
- 6+ repos / directories (planning, telemetry, detections, SOAR playbooks, two Purple exercises, capstone report).
- Measurable improvements in detection coverage and MTTD for chosen ATT&CK techniques.
- Ready-to-use detection rules + SOC runbooks + SOAR playbooks ‚Äî great portfolio evidence for DevSecOps / Detection Engineering roles.

Week 48.
By now, you‚Äôve already mastered GitOps security (Week 44), Zero Trust, Incident Response, Forensics, and Secure CI/CD.
Week 48 is where we shift gears into Multi-Cloud Security ‚Äî understanding AWS, Azure, and GCP security models together.
This makes you interview-proof for companies that aren‚Äôt AWS-only, since recruiters LOVE candidates who can compare across providers.

üìÖ Week 48: Multi-Cloud Security (AWS, Azure, GCP)
üéØ Goal
- Understand core differences in AWS, Azure, and GCP security models.
- Learn IAM, Networking, Logging, and Compliance across clouds.
- Deploy & secure workloads in multiple clouds.
- Deliver a Multi-Cloud Security Comparison Lab repo.

üîπ Day 1 ‚Üí Multi-Cloud IAM & Identity Security
Topics
- AWS IAM vs Azure AD vs GCP IAM.
- Service accounts (AWS Roles, GCP SA, Azure Managed Identity).
- Federation & SSO across clouds.
Practice
- Create least-privilege IAM role in AWS.
- Create Azure Managed Identity & assign to VM.
- Create GCP Service Account & bind minimal role.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è multicloud-iam-lab/ ‚Üí Repo with notes + Terraform for IAM setups.
Interview Qs
- Difference between AWS IAM Role vs GCP Service Account vs Azure Managed Identity?
- How do you implement least privilege across clouds?

üîπ Day 2 ‚Üí Multi-Cloud Networking & Security Groups
Topics
- AWS VPC vs Azure VNet vs GCP VPC.
- Security Groups vs NSGs vs Firewall Rules.
- Peering, Private Endpoints, Service-to-service access.
Practice
- Create secure VPC in each cloud with public + private subnets.
- Configure firewall: only SSH from your IP.
- Enable logging (VPC Flow Logs, NSG Logs, GCP Flow Logs).
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è multicloud-networking-lab/ ‚Üí Terraform repo creating VPC/VNet across clouds.
Interview Qs
- How do security groups differ in AWS, Azure, GCP?
- How do you secure multi-cloud networking?

üîπ Day 3 ‚Üí Logging & Monitoring Across Clouds
Topics
- AWS CloudTrail vs Azure Activity Logs vs GCP Audit Logs.
- Threat detection: GuardDuty vs Azure Security Center vs GCP Security Command Center.
- Centralized logging with ELK/SIEM.
Practice
- Enable CloudTrail + GuardDuty in AWS.
- Enable Azure Activity Logs + ASC.
- Enable GCP Audit Logs + SCC.
- Forward logs from all three ‚Üí single ELK dashboard.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è multicloud-logging-lab/ ‚Üí Repo with ELK setup + log pipelines.
Interview Qs
- How do you detect anomalous behavior across multi-cloud?
- Which cloud gives the best threat detection visibility?

üîπ Day 4 ‚Üí Multi-Cloud Compliance & Governance
Topics
- Compliance frameworks (PCI, HIPAA, SOC2) across clouds.
- Native tools:
	- AWS Config, Security Hub
	- Azure Policy, Blueprints
	- GCP Config Validator, Forseti Security
- Mapping compliance controls across providers.
Practice
- Enable AWS Config rule (no public S3).
- Enable Azure Policy (deny public storage).
- Enable GCP Validator (deny public buckets).
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è multicloud-compliance-lab/ ‚Üí Repo with policies + compliance reports.
Interview Qs
- What‚Äôs the difference between AWS Config and Azure Policy?
- How do you automate compliance across multi-cloud?

üîπ Day 5 ‚Üí Multi-Cloud Secrets & Key Management
Topics
- AWS KMS vs Azure Key Vault vs GCP KMS.
- Secrets management ‚Üí Vault across clouds.
- Encryption-at-rest + in-transit.
Practice
- Encrypt S3 (AWS), Blob (Azure), GCS bucket (GCP) with KMS keys.
- Store DB password in Vault ‚Üí deploy app across multi-cloud with same secrets manager.
Mini-Project
‚û°Ô∏è multicloud-secrets-lab/ ‚Üí Vault + KMS integration repo.
Interview Qs
- Difference between AWS KMS, Azure Key Vault, and GCP KMS?
- Why use Vault if cloud has its own secret manager?

üîπ Day 6 ‚Üí Capstone Project: Multi-Cloud Security Lab
Project ‚Üí ‚ÄúSecure Multi-Cloud Environment‚Äù
- AWS ‚Üí IAM, GuardDuty, Config.
- Azure ‚Üí Managed Identity, Security Center, Policy.
- GCP ‚Üí Service Accounts, SCC, Validator.
- Centralized Logging ‚Üí ELK dashboard.
- Compliance ‚Üí CIS mapping across all clouds.
Deliverables
- Repo ‚Üí multicloud-security-lab/
- Terraform/IaC scripts for AWS, Azure, GCP.
- Security reports + dashboards.
- README with comparison table + architecture diagram.
Interview Drill
- Walk me through your multi-cloud security setup.
- What‚Äôs the hardest challenge in multi-cloud DevSecOps?
- How do you enforce compliance across 3 providers?

üîπ Day 7 ‚Üí Wrap-up + Mock Interview
Tasks
